Throughout this difficult time, we want you to know that Strata Tattoo Lab still OPEN for business, and taking *every* precaution necessary to protect our clients and ourselves. -If you're feeling ill, please reschedule your appointment, there will NOT be a penalty regarding your retainer fee. - We are not taking walk-ins at this time, all tattoos must be done by *appointment only, to keep a minimum of less than 10 people in the studio at once. -We also ask that when you *do come in for your appointment, that you come ALONE and do not bring friends or family to watch. Slowing down:
These are uncertain and scary times.
I have experienced so many emotions in the past 24 hours.
Telling my 89 year old client whom i‚Äôve cooked for every Thursday for 2 years that I wouldn‚Äôt be coming this week was difficult. She asked if this meant I wouldn‚Äôt be cooking for her anymore. I told her of course I would cook for her again but right now I don‚Äôt want to put her or anyone else at risk. 
I‚Äôve been off for a day and a half and I already miss my routine and all the lovely interactions I get to have with people.
On a positive note, I have been cooking so much for myself and my partner with what we have one hand which has brought me so much joy.
I love cooking and I especially love cooking for other people. Finding a way to do that for money during a pandemic is going to be challenging but not impossible.
I‚Äôm trying to stay as present as I can and am committed to finding the light now mater how dark it may get.
Today I made birria de chivo among many other things.
I was reminded of how the best things take time and patience and how sharing love is always possible.
I‚Äôm here for you all if you need any support and happy to share recipes and tips.

Art is Work

Creating art is a valid career.

There seems to be this perception in our culture that art is not really a profession but more of a hobby. That creativity is a pastime, not a true vocation.

It‚Äôs no secret that many of us see our day jobs as monotonous, boring, and something that we only do because we may need rent money.  According to this worldview, art is optional but work is not ‚Äî therefore art cannot be work.

Our culture tends to believe that creating art or music is something that is only reserved for those lucky few who, for whatever reason, have too much time on their hands. In other words, being an artist is not a real job.  It is only for misfits or those who would not otherwise be able to function in polite society.

As @mattmucciaccio would say....
.
Get comfortable being uncomfortable.

This is chaos.
The world feels as tho it is in shambles.
People are without work.
Resources are dwindling.
Business are closing.

This is not great. But this is not ACTUALLY the end of the world.

Flip the switch in your head;
3-2-1...
What can this phase of chaos teach us? How can we use this time to GROW?

Let‚Äôs think about alllll the things we put off daily, weekly, monthly, just because we don‚Äôt have time...
-reading a new book
-learning a trade
-walking on the beach/enjoying nature
-having difficult conversations w/ loved ones
-meditation/yoga
-laundry... *ahem* (yes I‚Äôm talking to myself)

I can relate to those struggles. Isolation and I don‚Äôt get along... #sorrynotsorry

insta_description:
You can really get lost in your headspace during times of uncertainty. I must admit I have been hanging around in my head a little bit too much the last couple of days, letting my mind wander to the worst case scenario, entertaining all of the what if‚Äôs. Seeing people planning all of their ‚Äúquarantine days‚Äù schedules like it‚Äôs a well-oiled machine. Well, in our house most days consist of movies, playing dinosaurs, taking run-around breaks outside (steering clear of any other human, of course), prepping meals and helping tiny humans eat, then cleaning up, then doing it all over again. It has been a lot and I think all of the undue pressure is put on by my own expectations as a mom, what our days ‚Äúshould‚Äù look like.

Well, I have decided to officially throw that out the window and just enjoy my little babes, in whatever capacity that may look like. The stress of the world does not need to put pressure on me and my little family. I was letting it take hold, but not anymore. Not anymore. Cheers to getting a little sunshine break to remind you of all the good. The flowers are still blooming, the sky is still blue. We will be ok. We will come out on the other side of this thing just fine, like we always have, like we always will. He has got us, I‚Äôll let Him carry my worries from now on.

Be well.

My mom said she was leaving again today to go walk a rescue dog. She explained to me that not all dogs are as lucky as me to have a warm home and loving family. She also told me the story of when she adopted me as a puppy. Here are some pictures of Hershey the  four-year-old Doberman who is up for adoption at Animals Rule Rescue ( in the LA area ). She learned today that he jumps in the car and loves car rides. He even gave her kisses on the drive to the beach. He walks well on a leash and is housebroken. Hershey has seen the vet, is on high quality dog food, gets 2 medicated baths a week to help his coat come back in.  If you have any questions about Hershey or possibly adopting or fostering him or any other dogs please contact the rescue via e-mail at: info@animalsrule.org

insta_description:
How do you even start a post like this? Maybe with some facts. I live in San Francisco, and the whole Bay Area has just shut down with a 'shelter in place' order that keeps everyone at home. For me the current situation means a complete loss of income, and no work in sight - in fact I'm unsure how my work will look in the future. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Surviving in a city like San Francisco as a creative freelancer is hard on a regular day, right now it seems almost impossible. One thing I have had to do in the past, over and over again, is adapt to change. So that's what I'm doing now. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
For a lot of businesses the only option to survive this moment is taking things online, in whatever capacity possible. For some this may be entire new territory. This is where we can work together. Collaborate. Lift each other up. Come together in a world of social distancing. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
You have products you can sell online? You have no good photos of them? Let me help you. I have a small but perfectly formed home studio. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Send me your products and I can photograph them for you! ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
If you don't have a business, nothing to sell online, but maybe you want to help anyway - please share this with anyone who may need it. I need all the help I can get to get the word out and have some work coming in. We can do this, together. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Please stay safe and take good care of yourselves, people! We need each other right now. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

insta_description:
I know it‚Äôs really hard when our normal is snatched away. Our stability is gone. We‚Äôre living the unknown. 
The coronavirus has stolen the security of all we thought was beautiful and stable and leaves us scared, fragile, and more vulnerable than ever. 
But God.  He‚Äôs there. 
Even though we don‚Äôt have an end in sight right now, we need to choose hope. 
Am I letting this mess define me or refine me?

We need to replace our fear with empowering truths from God‚Äôs word. 
When we find ourselves in storms we can‚Äôt control, how do we respond with faith? Here are three encouraging truths to remember:

1. God has power over every storm.
If the wind and waves don‚Äôt concern Him, then they shouldn‚Äôt frighten you. You might not be able to change your situation, but you can choose to faithfully trust God in the middle of¬†it.

2. Fixing your eyes on Jesus leads to peace.
Are you looking at the size of the storm, or turning towards the One who can calm it? It‚Äôs only by focusing on God, who knows every outcome, that you can navigate any situation with His wisdom and peace.

3. Jesus is always in your¬†boat.
It‚Äôs easy to focus on your fears when you can‚Äôt control your future. But thankfully, Jesus knows your future, and He‚Äôs always by your side. And, He calls you to live by faith, not by sight.

Whenever you find yourself overwhelmed by life, you always have two choices: you can focus on your circumstances, or fix your eyes on Jesus.
If you choose to look to Jesus above everything else, you will begin to see that the storms you face are not nearly as powerful as the Savior choosing to walk through the storm alongside¬†you.

Stayed at mountain valley retreat last night with a few lovely hikers. The world has gotten pretty crazy lately so we have been doing our best not to share germs and have been camping in only small groups of two or three. The retreat center was lovely. Stayed in a trailer, was served home cooked meals, had a hot shower, got my laundry done, and was led through a much-needed yoga for hikers session in the morning by Chery. .
Slack-packed the 9 miles into Warner Springs this afternoon and will hike onwards tomorrow. It felt like we were flying as we hiked without our packs!
.

The gas station, lodge, and post office are open, but that‚Äôs about it. The restaurant and community centre are closed until further notice. Quality: Very Good 
Conclusion: Drink now; might be suitable for further aging.

insta_description:
I find myself going through each passing day with an overwhelming sense of anxiety and feeling of uncertainty. The world we know has been thrown out the window and we are all being forced to deal with an issue that transcends race, religion and politics. I take solace in the fact that many times these types of global events have the ability to bring the world together rather than drive us apart. This shall pass and we will overcome.
.
As an artist, I am able to find distraction in the activity I love most - photography. I started my career as a landscape photographer and no matter how large a production I work on these days, chasing light with nothing but my camera will always remain my favorite time behind the lens. When I‚Äôm out shooting landscapes I slow down and immerse myself in the scenery with the sole task of creating.
.
I shot this image two days ago looking out over the rugged Sonoma Coast. As I waited for the long exposure to finish, I watched the waves pound the shore and found that brief moment of peace I was looking for.
______________________________

insta_description:
When we spend so much time on our sofa, why not get one that will last?‚†Ä
‚†Ä
These are the 4 things to keep in mind when searching for a high-quality sofa that will stand the test of time:‚†Ä
‚†Ä
1 - Make sure it has a hardwood frame, not particle board or some other cheap material.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
2 - You want hand-tied springs for quality support over time, rather than none at all.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
3 - Quality cushions will be made of foam wrapped in down vs. just foam. You can test this by pushing down on the cushion. If it stays put when you press down, it will flatten over time and will quickly lose its visual appeal.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
4 - If you have the luxury of selecting your own fabric, this is also a huge bonus too since you can control the quality, the feel or "hand,‚Äù amount of ‚Äúrubs‚Äù (note: the longer the double-rubs, the longer the longevity), and if you have children or dogs, you can find stain-resistant or scrubbable fabrics!‚†Ä
‚†Ä
The image above features @LawsonFenning, one of my favorite go-to shops that design high-quality, customizable pieces that are hand-made here in Los Angeles. ‚†Ä
‚†Ä

insta_description:
I am scared.  Just like all of you.  But that doesn‚Äôt mean we are afraid.  We are not afraid to walk through those hospital doors and care for you.  Sure, we want the environment as safe as possible but we will be there.  We have all devised protocols.  We have all scoured the literature looking for the golden goose.  In the end, we need to find a way to inhibit the virus.  We know how the virus binds with its Spike protein via the ACER2 which is a receptor located on epithelial cells in the lung (type 2 pneumocyte), vascular endothelial cells, renal cells and small intestine.  We know a protease is needed to cleave the Spike protein for membrane fusion.  We know a viral RNA polymerase is needed for replication.  I say this because there are potential treatment options.  I say this to maintain our hope. For those that want to know, I will list the potential therapies below. 
1. Chloroquine/hydroxychloroquine (may inhibit viral entry into cells)
2. Remdesivir (inhibits viral RNA polymerase)
3. Lopinavir/ritonavir (inhibits protease/inhibits lover from metabolizing protease)
4. Favipiravir (inhibits viral RNA polymerase)
5. Ribavirin (inhibits viral synthesis and viral mRNA capping)
6. Make sure your nutrition is up to snuff with vitamins *bonus-there is thought we need to inhibit the cytokine storm.  It is an immune reaction that leads to a significant number of WBCs traveling throughout the body leading to hypotension due to blood vessel leakage and clogging of the alveoli.  2 drugs being studied here.  Sarilumab and tocilizumab (both inhibit the cytokine IL-6)

I write this to offer thought and to let you know efforts are being made.  I am not stating these work.  I am informing you of our thought process and our hope.  We can do better and we will for all of you and your families.  Healthcare teams!  Assemble.  Let‚Äôs go!  Let do this!  Together. insta_description:
The Hilbert Museum is currently closed due to the COVID-19 outbreak, but until we re-open, we're sharing images and stories from our current exhibitions. We look forward to seeing you when we are able to re-open!

Joseph Frey (1892-1977), "The Rite Spot," 1930s, oil on canvas. The Hilbert Collection.

Lionel Sternberger is reputed to have invented the cheeseburger in 1926 at the age of 16 when he was working as a fry cook at his father's Pasadena, California roadside sandwich shop, "The Rite Spot", and experimentally dropped a slab of American cheese on a sizzling hamburger.

As you can see in Joseph Frey's engaging painting from the 1930s, The Rite Spot also sold fresh oranges and a variety of other treats, including "hot and cold sandwiches of all kinds," Arrowhead ginger ale, chocolate malts, and Ko-Fan, a popular soda-fountain beverage of the time.

Frey was born in Walla Walla, Washington and opened his first art studio in San Francisco in 1915. After serving in World War I, he spent many years at sea working as a chef and studying painting. By the late 1920s he settled in Southern California where he lived and worked in Los Angeles, Palm Springs, and Santa Barbara. Frey is best known for his landscape paintings of Southern California's mountains and deserts.  #hilbertmuseum #hilbertmuseumofcaliforniaart #art #california #californiaart #californiaartist #californiaartists #museums #galleries #artmuseums #artgalleries #cheeseburger #theritespot #pasadena #losangeles #restaurants #food #hamburger #josephfrey #chapmanuniversity #chapmanu

Dear Clients, Colleagues and Friends,

First off, we hope that you and your families are safe and healthy during these difficult times. 
Like everyone else, we have been monitoring the reports coming from the Centers for Disease Control (CDC) and the Public Health Department of Santa Clara County regarding COVID-19.  This has been mandated by order of the Health Officer of Santa Clara County due to COVID-19. In summary, this order mandates that all persons shelter in-place until April 7, 2020 in order to reduce the spread of the COVID-19 Coronavirus.

In support of this mandate, Signature Events office will be closed and we will be modifying our office work schedules by working remotely to reduce the spread of COVID-19.  We will still be accessible via email and phone.  All client and vendor meetings will be done via conference call, Zoom, Google Hangout, etc. 
Signature Events will be back into the office on Wednesday, April 8, 2020.  For any questions or concerns, please feel free to contact us at 408.884.3786.

We are all in this together as a community and we must continue to support each other in any way that we can.

Respectfully, Christina Romero, CWC

Founder/CEO

The video pretty well encapsulates what I wanted to say but for those of you that must get drunk off word I‚Äôll fill your cup up.

Good friend and hockey brethren @tam234 invited me on this journey, he also helped with some of the rad action footage of our bike ride. He is a talented bicyclist and I got humbled. It‚Äôs not like I didn‚Äôt remember how to ride a bike, I remembered...but riding that dirty bastard twenty miles with a group of at least a thousand other like minded maniacs from Silverlake (Fountain and Sunset) to the Santa Monica Pier is a different ballgame.

But, that‚Äôs what we did. It usually starts at 3A with a nice police escort while we hold up traffic for whatever drunk disillusional fucks are out driving at the hour but with that greasy ass daylight savings springing us forward it began at 4A this day.

Was a bad ass time, and the beginning of a long day. It took us about two hours and some change to knock off that twenty mile ride, then I regained my composure and headed back to the Marathon Route to root on my fucking HOMIE @noblepeasant as he ran his first ever marathon.

That‚Äôs pretty much it, if you were there you could‚Äôve enjoyed in the delight of life with me that beautiful Los Angeles day but the majority of you weren‚Äôt {except you @gianniglock} (fucking rude) so I made this video so you could share in the joys and sorrows in what is just another fantastic day on this earth. .

This is just one of the benefits of this ancient Ayurvedic practice but it seems like the most important at this point in time.  A moist and lubricated nasal passage is inhospitable to foreign invaders and keeps you more resistant to viruses and allergens of all forms.  This practice is so easy to add to your daily routine that you may find yourself keeping with it for years.

You‚Äôll want high quality or food grade sesame oil. (No toasted oil or with chili‚Äôs added, pretty please). First thing in the morning, with *very* clean hands, place several drops of sesame oil in each nostril so it feels good and oiled up.  Gently wipe the nose on the outer edges to remove any excess and you‚Äôre good to go.

I recommend twice a day during cold season but at least once a day all year long.

May it of benefit.

Tracy

insta_description:
Roseville Amtrak Station
An Eastbound Union Pacific freight train led by UP 7868 GE AC45CCTE past the Amtrak Station platform in Roseville, California. Roseville is the home of Union Pacific‚Äôs Davis Yard. This large hump yard handles almost all of Union Pacific freight trains in northern California.  On the east end of the yard, and just east of the Roseville train station (walking distance) is a covered train watching platform located on city land.  The no-thrills platform is located on the north side of the tracks and has a view of all trains that travel over both Donner Pass and the Valley Sub (which runs north to Dunsmuir, CA). The locomotive shops are also within view (located just west of the station, also on the north side of the yard), in between trains Union Pacific does move power around, most of the time passing the platform in both directions as a slow speed.  Some power is turned on the wye located just east of the platform where the Valley Sub and the Roseville Sub meet.

insta_description:
Here is a little bit of hand sanitizer for the economy; for those wondering what‚Äôs going on.

Since the Federal Reserve made the announcement yesterday that they were dropping the Mortgage Interest a full percent down to almost 0% in an effort to restore calm and provide market stimulus among coronavirus-spurred. Our phones have been ringing off the hook with borrowers wanting to take advantage of the 0% interest.

We wanted to shed some light on these changes and how they affect you, the consumer. 
The Federal Reserve dropped the rate they lend money to the banks. The banks still have a 'Margin' that is added to produce the final rate; the margin varies depending on factors of each barrower.  Could mortgage rates go lower?  Yes.  They probably will, but not by 0.5%, and not in a day.  They could also go higher.  One place they're not going is 0%. The lowering of the rate by the feds has created  fantastic timing for refinancing or purchasing but the market is currently very volatile so rates have not seen the drop that you would expect yet.

When the rates do drop for the consumer it may be for a very short period of time and it‚Äôs important that you are ready to lock your loan right away. 
This is our way of making sure you don‚Äôt miss out on the lowest rates by allowing you to have your loan ready to close and waiting for the best possible pricing day instead of waiting and possibly missing out on the lowest rates in the history of our country!

insta_description:
Sukhasana aka Easy pose (or sitting cross legged)

Today did not go as planned. I woke up at 3:30am to get my 5am bus to San Diego, only to find that my flight had been cancelled. I then headed straight to LA for a flight back home from there tonight, meaning a 9 hour wait in LAX (because everything is closing in LA and I'm not taking my luggage for a tour of Hollywood boulevard). So here I am, first in line to check in my bag and practicing yoga on my suitcase.

My point here: you can either roll with the punches and just be happy you have your health and can still get about. Or you can be miserable (like the couple in the background), and only focus on the negatives of the world around you, leading to additional stress on your body.

Stay safe everyone. But also try stay happy and look on the bright side of things! üíú

P.S. Yes I got many weird looks for doing yoga while balancing on  my suitcase.

insta_description:
‚ÄúWHAT A TIME TO BE ALIVE‚Äù
12‚Äùx18‚Äù ink and acrylic on paper
$100
.
.
With @warhorsetattoo closed, I am trying to pivot and spend my time creating with positive intent. Although tattooing can not be translated to an online form, I am hoping to continue to connect and be inspired using this platform. To that end, I am going to be painting a piece a day while the shelter-in-place order is in effect here in my home of the Bay Area. .
.
The work will likely be mostly calligraphy but probably with some other stuff thrown in along the way. Each piece will be for sale, I will price them and give dimensions in each post.
.
.
Not only will the sales of these works help me pay my bills while I‚Äôm unable to tattoo, I will also be donating 10% of all sales to a charity or charities. I am still researching how my donations can be most effective, but 10% if everything is going to a good cause. Trying to keep thing positive, and work toward helping causes bigger than myself.
.
.
I will be making pieces in a variety of sizes and price ranges, hoping that anyone who is lucky enough to have work and/or finances enough to do so, can access the work. I will also be doing portions of the paintings on Instagram live to further the connection and reach I‚Äôm hoping to find through this project. .
.
Even if you cannot purchase any of the works I have created, feel free to join in on the live sessions and interact with me online, as well as share any questions you have about the work. And, the easiest way to help support the project is by just sharing it with your online network, to keep expanding its reach. I‚Äôm hoping to spend this time locked-down doing something positive, creative, and community building. Stay safe, and hope you can connect along the way as we all power through this challenging time!

insta_description:
the CDC says ‚Äúolder people and people with chronic medical conditions‚Äù are at the highest risk for contracting COVID-19 ‚Äî i have MS. to add onto that, the medication i get infused once every four weeks significantly weakens/slows my immune system, so that it can‚Äôt attack the myelin in my brain and cause more lesions. if i contract coronavirus, i am a member of the high risk group that could very easily die. think that‚Äôs a harsh way to say it? good. i take my life seriously.

let me say it again ‚Äî i. could. die. if i contract COVID-19. i‚Äôm not being dramatic, i‚Äôm being real; telling the truth. I AM ‚Äúthe vulnerable‚Äù population. if you‚Äôre seeing this, you know me. you know someone who could die during this pandemic. #wearethevulnerable

i am astronomically frustrated to see people my age continuing to go in public for non-essential outings & ignore quarantines/shelter in place orders, just to interact with folks like me who don‚Äôt look disabled or sick, but can & will die due to their peer‚Äôs carelessness. BE ACCOUNTABLE. BE COMPASSIONATE. BE UNDERSTANDING.

with that said, it is MORE THAN OKAY to be upset if & when things we were all looking forward to get cancelled. my heart absolutely aches for my peers at my alma mater who had their commencement cancelled. trips? gone. new jobs? slashed. schooling? over for the semester. but do you know what would (& will be) worse than losing these things? losing your friends and family to COVID-19. you know someone who is high risk. & if you don‚Äôt, you know me. i am high risk. i will die if i catch corona & don‚Äôt act in time.

the fact is, we are all susceptible to illness. the chronically ill know this fact better than most. but now YOU have a part to play in our demise. this isn‚Äôt a joke. it isn‚Äôt something to be taken lightly. you aren‚Äôt on vacation. we are not disposable. we are not invisible.

look at yourself, & the ripple effect you have on the people around you. do your part. please.

insta_description:
Social Distancing... These photos were taken last week, just before the travel bans, event cancellations, business closures, and panic buying became widespread here in the States... Before many of us began the process of isolating ourselves at home... Before some of us began to face the reality of layoffs, extended time off work without pay, and the fear of economic, health related, or other hardships.

These challenging situations have the propensity to bring out the best and worst in people.  The situation is dire and will likely get worse before it gets better... but in time it will pass and we will recover.  Of this I am certain. 
In the meantime, let‚Äôs do what we can to help one another.  Even if it‚Äôs just little things.  Show some appreciation and consideration for the health care professionals, firefighters, peace officers, and others who are doing their best to keep us safe and healthy.  The postal, UPS, and other transportation and logistics workers, who ensure that packages are delivered to our doors and that food and medical supplies make it to our hospitals and stores.  The grocery store and other retail workers who come to work so that we are able to purchase what we need.  The elderly and others who are at a greater risk of severe illness or death.  And so many others who are working hard to get through this and figure things out.  I‚Äôm not talking about grand gestures here (and certainly not hugs). Just the little things, a kind word, not hoarding supplies, delivering groceries to those who cannot get them for themselves (provided you take measures not infect them or yourself in the process), etc.

And do remember to have a Happy St. Patrick‚Äôs Day! ‚òòÔ∏è This Irish/Mexican will be spending a quiet evening at home with my pup, my girl, and a bit of Mezcal and Irish Whiskey. üì∑: @tabosco

We regret the necessity for posting this. 
As the COVID-19 virus continues to impact our (worldwide) communities, we here at Los Angeles Guinea Pig Rescue are taking steps to protect our volunteers and the public. 
Please take a moment the read the changes we are implementing as it may impact you. 
Effective immediately: ‚Ä¢we will be strictly enforcing our existing ***APPOINTMENT ONLY*** policy. Appointments will be greatly reduced with staggered time slots. ‚Ä¢during these free health check/nail trim appointments, we can no longer allow families into the facility. We strongly encourage only one family member to bring their piggie in for their APPOINTMENT. ‚Ä¢no baths will be scheduled. ALL currently scheduled baths need to be canceled. ‚Ä¢no tours or VISITORS will be allowed during this time. ‚òπÔ∏è ‚Ä¢ADOPTION appointments will be reduced. ‚Ä¢SUPPLY pickups are still welcome. ¬°BY APPOINTMENT! 
We are doing our best to continue to help the Guinea Pig community and provide a healthier environment for everyone involved. 
We appreciate your continued support and look forward to getting back to our regular routine here at the ranch. 
Please don‚Äôt hesitate to contact us via email:

insta_description:
O R A N G E üçä B L O S S O M...a sweet, delicate and intoxicating scent...by far my favorite hydrosol. After a difficult and concerning week in California, at the beginning of the pandemic, I was immediately reminded that Nature and the Plant World are such powerful healers. I was in total awe of the abundant, edible, aromatic and medicinal landscape that covers Southern California, a microclimate very foreign to me. As stressful as it was being so far from home I felt strangely safe, comforted and protected by many plant allies not to mention the peaceful, friendly community of Ojai and the love and support of my dearest, closest friends.
I am happy to say...I made it home safely, back in Vermont, my sweet, safe haven just in the nick of time. üôè

insta_description:
In light of the most recent recommendations from California state officials and our concern for the health of our staff and patrons, Adkins Family Vineyards will not be open for tasting and tours until further notice. We will, however, have staff available on-site to facilitate the pick-up of any wine. We will remain open Saturday and Sunday 11am-4pm. Our wine club managemnt will continue to be available to assist you at 916-619-7060 during our business hours.
‚Ä¢
In order to encourage social distancing and facilitate for those who are taking the necessary measure to self-quarantine, we will also be offering an additional 10% off any order made online. This means:
‚Ä¢
Wine Club members will receive 35% off orders of any size.
‚Ä¢
Non-members will receive:
- 10% off 1-5 bottles - 20% off 6-11 bottles - 30% off orders of a case or more
‚Ä¢
We hope that this will help to offset the shipping costs for those who are staying inside during this difficult time. You can place your order (for pick up or delivery) at AdkinsFamilyVineyards.com
‚Ä¢
We will continue to keep you all posted as things develop, and please continue to check our Facebook and Instagram pages for the latest news regarding this matter. Until then, please stay safe and feel free to reach out to us directly with any questions.
‚Ä¢
Stay Healthy and Cheers,
Adkins Family Vineyards

Checking in üëãüèΩ. How‚Äôs everyone doing? I‚Äôm doing well...trying to be really intentional about not only boosting my physical immune system but my emotional one, too. ‚òÄÔ∏è
‚òÄÔ∏è‚òÄÔ∏è‚òÄÔ∏è‚òÄÔ∏è
There are so many health benefits associated with the outdoors, sunshine, nature, exercise, grounding, no electronics, music, fresh air, water, journaling, and prayer/meditation. Now more than ever...as we‚Äôre constantly bombarded with all things fear-inducing...we need to be mindfully focusing on healthy mindsets and de-stressing. Stress causes high-cortisol and inflammation levels which decrease the immune system, so keep decompressing, y‚ÄôallüëáüèΩ.
‚òÄÔ∏è‚òÄÔ∏è‚òÄÔ∏è‚òÄÔ∏è
1) Obviously exercise is HUGE for both the physical & mental aspects. Start a daily routine (all experts are suggesting daily routines right now) of walking, jogging, outdoor workouts (or indoor), etc. More on this one later...we all know the benefits are insane!
2) Get out in the sunshine. I can‚Äôt stress this enough. Vitamin D is a crucial ingredient for overall health; protects against inflammation, lowers high blood pressure, helps muscles, improves brain function & may even protect against some cancers. Sun exposure also has a huge impact on depression/mood, seasonal affective disorder and sleep quality.
3) Grounding. Do things that ‚Äòground‚Äô you back to the earth, like walking barefoot in the grass or sand. You can also lie down in the grass/sand to ground your full body (and do it in the sunshine for extra benefits!). You can also dip your bare feet (or swim) in water...such as a clear lake or the ocean.
4) Prayer/Meditation have many health benefits contributing to a calmer state of mind, more positivity, better sleep, lower stress levels/anxiety, lower blood pressure, etc. More on this one later too.
‚òÄÔ∏è‚òÄÔ∏è‚òÄÔ∏è‚òÄÔ∏è
I could list the benefits of music, no electronics, journaling, etc. too...but you‚Äôre seeing the pattern here. These are all amazing ways to take care of your mental state right now, as well as your physical body. At a time when things are so uncertain, let‚Äôs not only be kind to one another, but to ourselves. Love y‚Äôall, I‚Äôm truly praying for you, & I‚Äôm in this with you.‚ù§Ô∏è
